        {
            "id": "e12af7f819d3445592f3e",
            "questionText": "A 1500 kg car travels on a circular racetrack with a radius of 500 m. Initially, the car moves at 30 m/s, but then its speed is doubled to 60 m/s while maintaining the same radius. Given these conditions, what is the frequency (in Hz) of the car's motion at the new speed?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "100e56a6beb94ae2b4b6d",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by connecting the car's linear speed to its angular speed. Which formula correctly relates the linear speed $!$v$!$ to the angular speed $!$\\omega$!$ and radius $!$r$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f08dbfc4-7ece-47af-8c8f-7609d1f384aa"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = r\\omega$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\omega = r/v$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = 2\\pi r\\omega$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "53e0373b0314489aa07e1",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now using the relation between linear and angular speed, compute the angular speed $!$\\omega$!$ when the car's new speed is $!$60\\,m/s$!$ and the radius is $!$500\\,m$!$. (Divide the linear speed by the radius.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.12"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "rad/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f08dbfc4-7ece-47af-8c8f-7609d1f384aa"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "f98acf35a7224375aab8d",
                    "stepText": "Now that we have the angular speed, let's identify the formula for the period $!$T$!$ (the time for one complete revolution) in terms of angular speed. Which option correctly represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a51157a0-fd9c-46a1-ac03-cc47674195b0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{2\\pi}{\\omega}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\omega\\,2\\pi$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{\\omega}{2\\pi}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "a70003fa44984041a9383",
                    "stepText": "Using the formula for the period, compute the period $!$T$!$ by dividing $!$2\\pi$!$ by the angular speed $!$\\omega$!$ you calculated. What is the period in seconds?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "52.36"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a51157a0-fd9c-46a1-ac03-cc47674195b0"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "8d6b016eb40a421ba4ea8",
                    "stepText": "Next, let's identify the relationship between the period and frequency. Which of the following correctly expresses frequency $!$f$!$ in terms of the period $!$T$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "24604eeb-cbe5-47fa-8481-aea6fc9d1ab0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = \\frac{1}{T}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = \\frac{T}{1}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6b788693224542358c172",
                    "stepText": "Finally, calculate the frequency by taking the reciprocal of the period you found. What is the frequency in Hz?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
